    <h1>OCTO FINISSIMO TOUR&#xAD;BIL&#xAD;LON CHRONO&#xAD;GRAPH SKELE&#xAD;TON AU&#xAD;TO&#xAD;MATIC</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200911/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-11"><time>2020-09-11</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>The Bvlgari Octo Finissimo (above) is at its ul­tra-thin game again and has bro­ken its sixth record in just as many years.</p>
    <p>Housed in a case just 7.4mm thick, it is the world’s thinnest tour­bil­lon chrono­graph.</p>
    <p>The skele­tonised move­ment has 388 com­po­nents but mea­sures only 3.55mm thick.</p>
    <p>De­spite the ra­zor-thin di­men­sions, it boasts a col­umn wheel and a ver­ti­cal clutch, and has a power re­serve of 52 hours.</p>
    <p>Fash­ioned from sandblaste­d Grade 5 ti­ta­nium, the time­piece has a trans­par­ent case back, the bet­ter to ad­mire the move­ment.</p>
    <p>Only 50 pieces are avail­able, with price upon re­quest.</p>

